<b>Jon Halliday</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../575/13575.xml">
historian</link> of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../115/14115.xml">
Russia</link> and was a former Senior Visiting Research Fellow at <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../483/158483.xml">
King's College London</link></university>
.<p>

Halliday authored a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../562/7370562.xml">
biography</link> of filmmaker <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../137/102137.xml">
Douglas Sirk</link></actor>
</person>
 and has written and edited seven other books. He and his wife, <writer wordnetid="110794014" confidence="0.9173553029164789">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../658/1156658.xml">
Jung Chang</link></writer>
, live in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../200/94200.xml">
Notting Hill</link></site>
, West <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/17867.xml">
London</link></village>
. Together they researched and wrote the highly popular biography of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../527/19527.xml">
Mao</link>,  which received great praise as well as serious criticism and spurred lively debate in the academic community.</p>
